Preheat your #oven{} to 180°C. Pop the @diced butternut squash{200%g} on a
#baking tray{} and drizzle over a little @olive oil{}. Season with @salt{} and
@pepper{}. Toss to coat, spread out and roast on the top shelf of your oven
until soft and golden, ~{30-35%minutes}.

Meanwhile, cut the @cherry plum tomatoes{200}(in half) and pop in a #large
bowl{}. Peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove}(peeled and grated) (or use a
#garlic press{}). Add to the tomatoes along with the @red wine vinegar{6%tbsp},
@sugar{¼%tsp} (if using), a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{} and a drizzle of
@olive oil{}. Set aside.

When the butternut squash has been in the oven for ~{15%minutes}, remove the
tray and give the squash a good toss. Push the squash to one side of the tray
and pop the tomatoes on the other side. Return to the oven to cook for the
remaining ~{15-20%minutes}, until the squash is golden and the tomatoes are
beginning to colour and burst.

In the meantime, heat a splash of @olive oil{} in a #small frying pan{} over
medium-low heat. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(peeled and thinly
sliced) and add to the pan with a pinch of @salt{}. Slowly cook the onion,
stirring occasionally, until soft and beginning to colour, ~{8-10%minutes}.
Meanwhile, pop your #kettle{} on to boil.

Pick the @basil leaves{12}(picked from stalks) and finely chop (discard the
stalks). Finely chop the @chives{1%bunch}(finely chopped) and the
@walnuts{20%g}(finely chopped). Zest the @lemon{½}(zested) then cut in half. In
a #small bowl{}, mix together the basil, chives, walnuts, three-quarters of the
@hard Italian style cheese{40%g}(grated), the lemon zest, the @olive oil{3%tbsp}
and @water{1%tbsp}. Season to taste with lemon juice, salt and pepper. Pesto
made!

Pour the water from the kettle into a #large saucepan{}. Bring back to the boil
on high heat and add a pinch of @salt{}. Stir in the @fusilli{160%g} and cook
until al dente, around ~{9%minutes}. Once cooked, drain in a #colander{}. Return
to the pan (off the heat) and drizzle with a little oil to stop it sticking
together.

> 'Al dente' simply means the pasta is cooked through but has a tiny bit of
> firmness left in the middle.

Once everything is cooked, stir the pesto and onion into the pasta. Gently mix
in the roasted tomatoes, butternut squash and any roasting juices from the
tray. Season to taste with more lemon juice, salt and pepper if needed. Finally,
stir in the @wild rocket{20%g} and allow to wilt. Divide between your plates
and sprinkle over the remaining cheese. Enjoy!

> Packed with fresh and vibrant vegetables combined with a walnut pesto this
> dish is a veggie winner. Pesto originates from the city of Genoa and this
> Italian inspiration is the flavour that underpins this tasty treasure. Make
> sure you finish it with a sprinkling of hard Italian cheese this will
> compliment the nutty pesto and top off a great tasting dish.

